    mecCaseEyebrow: "Case study",
    mecCaseTitle: "Fake E-commerce — Redis cart, Postgres orders",
    mecCaseLede: "A production-minded Next.js storefront where I started with Redis JSON blobs for order speed, then migrated to Postgres + Prisma on Neon for relational integrity—without changing the public API.",
    mecCaseBack: "← Back to portfolio",
    mecCaseProblemTitle: "1. Problem",
    mecCaseProblemP1: "v1 stored orders as Redis JSON blobs keyed by Clerk userId (orders:user:{userId}). That was fast to ship and fine for a demo checkout—but it broke down when I needed relational integrity, per-line-item queries, and an admin view over all orders.",
    mecCaseProblemP2: "Cart data stayed the right fit for Redis: session-scoped, high-churn key/value with no joins. Orders needed rows, foreign keys, and migrations. The migration had to swap the persistence adapter behind order-store.ts while keeping REST and GraphQL contracts identical.",
    mecCaseArchTitle: "2. Architecture",
    mecCaseArchIntro: "Two stores on purpose—each matches its access pattern:",
    mecCaseArchBullet1: "Cart — /api/cart/[sessionId] on Redis (in-memory fallback without REDIS_URL).",
    mecCaseArchBullet2: "Orders — /api/orders and GraphQL createOrder via Prisma; scoped by Clerk userId.",
    mecCaseArchBullet3: "Deploy — Neon pooled DATABASE_URL; prisma migrate deploy runs before next build on Vercel.",
    mecCaseMigrationTitle: "3. The migration",
    mecCaseMigrationIntro: "Four commits, same day—schema first, adapter swap, production bug fix, then docs:",
    mecCaseCommit1: "— Bootstrap Prisma 6 with Order + OrderItem schema, Docker Compose Postgres for local dev, initial migration.",
    mecCaseCommit2: "— Replace Redis order-store with Prisma adapter; map models to existing Order type; Redis stays for cart only. 45/45 tests green.",
    mecCaseCommit3: "— Fix duplicate order creation on /checkout/success (race condition deep-dive below).",
    mecCaseCommit4: "— README documents Redis cart vs Postgres orders and the migration narrative.",
    mecCaseMigrationNote: "Before the adapter swap I locked Redis behavior with commit 9668a49 so the test suite would catch regressions during the Prisma cutover.",
    mecCaseRaceTitle: "4. Race condition deep-dive",
    mecCaseRaceIntro: "After Postgres went live, checkout success sometimes created two orders for one cart. The bug lived in a useEffect on /checkout/success—not in Prisma. That’s the kind of issue that separates “it works on my machine” from production-aware React.",
    mecCaseRaceCauseTitle: "Root cause",
    mecCaseRaceCause1: "The effect depended on [addOrder, clearCart, total, cart, setOrderPaid, sendEvent]—unstable references on every render.",
    mecCaseRaceCause2: "hasSubmitted.current = true ran in .finally() after the async addOrder call—too late if the effect re-fired first.",
    mecCaseRaceCause3: "total was derived from async fetchProducts(), so dependency churn retriggered the effect while the first submission was still in flight.",
    mecCaseRaceFixTitle: "Fix",
    mecCaseRaceFix1: "Set hasSubmitted.current = true synchronously before addOrder.",
    mecCaseRaceFix2: "Snapshot cart items at submit time (cart.map(...)) to avoid stale closures.",
    mecCaseRaceFix3: "Replace async product fetch with computeOrderTotal() from static catalog data.",
    mecCaseRaceFix4: "Depend only on [cart.length]—fire once when the cart hydrates; reset guard on API failure.",
    mecCaseRaceLink: "View full diff on GitHub →",
    mecCaseOutcomesTitle: "5. Outcomes",
    mecCaseOutcome1: "45/45 tests passing after the Prisma adapter swap (Vitest unit + integration).",
    mecCaseOutcome2: "Live smoke test — sign in, add to cart, complete checkout; order appears in /my-purchases backed by Neon rows.",
    mecCaseOutcome3: "Production URL with Clerk auth, SSG/ISR catalog, and Playwright checkout E2E in CI:",
    mecCaseOutcome4: "Accessibility — Lighthouse 100 on home, products, PDP, and cart after landmark and labeling fixes.",
