    miniJobOutcome: "Interaction-heavy job board with tested filter logic, multi-page flows, and CI-backed quality gates.",
    miniJobBulletFilter: "Filter logic — Pure filter/sort module decoupled from the DOM; unit-tested in Node.",
    miniJobBulletFlows: "Product flows — Search, filters, saved jobs, detail modals/pages; theme and grid/list prefs in localStorage.",
    miniJobBulletCi: "CI — GitHub Actions: JS syntax checks, JSON schema validation, and filter unit tests.",
    miniJobBulletE2e: "E2E — Playwright happy path: search → save job → saved jobs modal.",
    miniJobImpact: "Impact: Recruiters can search, filter, save jobs, and verify the flow via Playwright—not just scroll a static list.",
    miniJobMore: "Engineering decisions on the card—testable filter architecture, product flows, CI, and E2E—not just a styled job list.",
    mjbCaseEyebrow: "Case study",
    mjbCaseTitle: "Mini Job Board — testable filters, shareable URL state",
    mjbCaseLede: "A vanilla-JavaScript job board where the engineering story isn't the UI—it's the architecture under it: a filter/sort module that has no idea the DOM exists, URL query params used as the single source of truth for filters, and a no-framework stack chosen on purpose and backed by tests.",
    mjbCaseBack: "← Back to portfolio",
    mjbCaseProblemTitle: "1. Problem",
    mjbCaseProblemP1: "Most junior frontend demos show a static list and stop there. I wanted interaction-heavy product behavior—real-time search, combined filters, sorting, saved jobs, and multi-page flows—without reaching for React or a build step. The risk with vanilla JS is that everything collapses into one DOM-coupled file that you can't test.",
    mjbCaseProblemP2: "So the real problem was architectural: keep the filtering logic pure and unit-testable, make filtered views shareable and deep-linkable, and treat the absence of a framework as a deliberate engineering choice rather than a missing dependency.",
    mjbCaseArchTitle: "2. Architecture",
    mjbCaseArchIntro: "Logic lives in shared modules; pages stay thin. State derives from data, not the other way around:",
    mjbCaseArchBullet1: "scripts/filter-logic.mjs — pure filter/sort helpers, unit-tested in Node, importable without a browser.",
    mjbCaseArchBullet2: "app.js — wires inputs to the module, reads/writes the URL, and renders derived slices of state.",
    mjbCaseArchBullet3: "Shared scripts — site-header.js, jobs-fetch-error.js, and validate-jobs.mjs reused across pages and CI.",
    mjbCaseFilterTitle: "3. The filter module",
    mjbCaseFilterIntro: "Everything that decides which jobs show up lives in scripts/filter-logic.mjs as pure functions. They take data and a state object and return a new array—no DOM reads, no globals—so they can be unit-tested in Node with node --test.",
    mjbCaseFilterComposeTitle: "Composable filters",
    mjbCaseFilterCompose1: "applyJobFilters(jobs, state) chains type, seniority, salary, and free-text search, then hands off to sortJobs.",
    mjbCaseFilterCompose2: "Search spans title, company, and location; each filter narrows an immutable copy, never the source array.",
    mjbCaseFilterCompose3: "sortJobs supports newest (by id), company A–Z, and remote-first (remote → hybrid → on-site, then company).",
    mjbCaseFilterSalaryTitle: "The salary-band edge case",
    mjbCaseFilterSalaryIntro: "Salaries arrive as messy strings (\"€3k–5k / year\", \"5k-8k\"). parseSalaryMonthlyUsd normalizes them to a monthly USD range—dividing yearly figures by 12 and converting EUR—then a band matches if the ranges overlap, not if one contains the other:",
    mjbCaseFilterSalaryNote: "Overlap (not containment) is the right rule: a \"3k–5k\" job should still surface under the \"5k–8k\" band because its range crosses the boundary. That kind of decision is trivial to verify when the logic is a pure function.",
    mjbCaseUrlTitle: "4. URL as the single source of truth",
    mjbCaseUrlIntro: "Filter state lives in the URL, not just in memory. That makes any filtered view shareable and deep-linkable—paste /?type=remote&seniority=senior&q=Developer and the board loads already filtered. Two small functions keep the URL and the controls in sync.",
    mjbCaseUrlReadTitle: "Reading state in (defensively)",
    mjbCaseUrlRead1: "readFiltersFromUrl() parses URLSearchParams on load and accepts both q and search for the query.",
    mjbCaseUrlRead2: "normalizeUrlFilter lowercases, trims, dash-joins, and validates each value against an allow-list Set—junk params are ignored, not rendered.",
    mjbCaseUrlWriteTitle: "Writing state out (without history spam)",
    mjbCaseUrlWrite1: "Only non-default values are written, so the URL stays clean (no ?type=all&sort=newest noise).",
    mjbCaseUrlWrite2: "history.replaceState (not pushState) avoids polluting the back stack on every keystroke; it only writes when the URL actually changes.",
    mjbCaseUrlWrite3: "A popstate listener re-reads the URL, re-syncs the dropdown labels, and re-applies filters—so browser back/forward restores the exact view.",
    mjbCaseVanillaTitle: "5. Vanilla depth, on purpose",
    mjbCaseVanillaIntro: "No framework and no build step is the feature here, not a shortcut. It forces—and demonstrates—command of the platform: DOM, events, history, storage, and module boundaries without a library smoothing over them.",
    mjbCaseVanilla1: "State without a store — an in-memory jobs array is the source of truth; the UI renders derived slices (filteredJobs, paginated batches).",
    mjbCaseVanilla2: "Persistence without a backend — theme, grid/list view, saved IDs, applied IDs, and the collapsed-filters preference all live in localStorage.",
    mjbCaseVanilla3: "Multi-page flows — index listing, job-details.html?id=, and saved-jobs.html share header and fetch-error modules instead of duplicating logic.",
    mjbCaseVanilla4: "Resilience — a fetch-failure banner and empty states with one-click reset, so the board degrades gracefully on a slow or broken network.",
    mjbCaseVanillaNote: "The deliberate trade-off: device-local persistence and client-side filtering, with a clear upgrade path to a real API and server-side pagination. Vanilla multi-page depth is the story—so a React rewrite is explicitly out of scope.",
    mjbCaseOutcomesTitle: "6. Outcomes",
    mjbCaseOutcome1: "Filter logic is unit-tested in isolation (tests/filter-logic.test.mjs via node --test)—no DOM, no browser needed.",
    mjbCaseOutcome2: "11 Playwright E2E scenarios cover search/save, the saved-jobs page, fetch-error banners, URL-state load/update, pagination, and apply tracking.",
    mjbCaseOutcome3: "CI runs JS syntax checks, JSON schema validation of data/jobs.json, unit tests, and E2E (npm run ci:full).",
    mjbCaseOutcome4: "Live on GitHub Pages—zero build, instant deploy:",
